{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"fab4f7bc-9f4f-4e2c-b52f-f500b7cf7af8","content":"The best approach is **`dotnet-trace`** with the `cpu-sampling` profile. Here's the workflow:\n\n**1. Install the tool inside the pod:**\n```bash\nkubectl exec -it <pod> -- bash\ndotnet tool install -g dotnet-trace\nexport PATH=\"$PATH:$HOME/.dotnet/tools\"\n```\n\n**2. Collect the trace (30s example):**\n```bash\ndotnet-trace collect -p $(pgrep -f dotnet) --profile cpu-sampling --duration 00:00:00:30\n```\n\n**3. Copy the `.nettrace` file out:**\n```bash\nkubectl cp <pod>:/path/to/trace.nettrace ./trace.nettrace\n```\n\n**4. Analyze** in Visual Studio, VS Code (`.NET Profile Visualizer` extension), or PerfView on Windows. You can also convert to speedscope format for browser-based viewing:\n```bash\ndotnet-trace convert trace.nettrace --format Speedscope\n```\n\n**Tips:**\n- If you can't install tools (read-only filesystem), use a **sidecar** or the [dotnet-monitor](https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/core/diagnostics/dotnet-monitor) container image instead.\n- For production-safe collection, prefer `dotnet-monitor` — it exposes an HTTP API for on-demand trace collection without exec.\n- `--duration` keeps the trace bounded; avoid open-ended collection in prod.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"d14b332a-8d22-47a7-81da-42b24b51991c","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking for guidance on collecting a CPU trace from a .NET 8 app running in a Kubernetes pod on Linux. This is a knowledge/advice question, not a code change task. I should provide a concise, practical answer.","outputTokens":420,"requestId":"9811:13E5E7:C71115:E88384:69F4025A"},"id":"ee381191-9006-4e33-af97-e62eff55f770","timestamp":"2026-05-01T01:31:17.029Z","parentId":"f134ea3b-1612-40fe-8885-4113ef6b38d0"}
